article.description:
Shameka Christon had 20 points,
and Arkansas (No. 21 ESPN, USA Today, No. 23 AP) beat physical Alabama 53-48 Thursday in the
Southeastern Conference tournament.
article.headline: Vaughn provides  Lady Razorbacks with a lift
article.linkText: Arkansas gets physical  with Alabama in SEC tourney
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansas hasn't relied on
freshman Rochelle Vaughn often this season, but that didn't stop
her on Thursday.

	   Vaughn's six points near the end of the game separated the Lady Razorbacks (No. 21 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) from Alabama and led the way for a 53-48 victory
in the first round of the Southeastern Conference Women's
Tournament at Alltel Arena.

	 "Rochelle Vaughn could be the player of the game," Arkansas
coach Gary Blair said. "She gives us an energy in transition. She
hit a three-point play that may have been the play of the game."

	   Arkansas, who beat Alabama three times this year and for the
first time in three tries at the SEC Tournament, faces LSU (No. 5, No. 6) in
the quarterfinals at 2:30 p.m. Friday.

	   Vaughn provided the spark while senior India Lewis, who injured
her back near the end of the first half, struggled to make 3-of-11
from the field.

	   Arkansas (21-9) led 39-37 when Vaughn grabbed a defensive
rebound on the run and went all the way for a three-point play with
a deft move in the lane. Alabama's Manisha Redus was called for
blocking on the play.

	"I wasn't planning on taking the shot," said Vaughn, who
averages 3.2 points per game. "I was going to pass the ball to
Lakishia Harper, but I decided to take the shot myself.
Fortunately, it worked out for us."

	   Beth Vice, who led Alabama (13-15) with 16 points, countered
with a jumper, but Vaughn came back with the 3-pointer to give
Arkansas a 45-39 lead.

	   Arkansas' Shameka Christon didn't struggle, making nine of 15
shots for 20 points and six rebounds. Christon scored 25 in the
regular-season finale against Alabama on Sunday.

	   Dana Cherry was the only other Arkansas player in double figures
with 10 points, as the Lady Razorbacks made less than 40 percent
(21 of 56) of its shots for the fourth time in five games.

	  "(Alabama's) defense tonight was the best defensive effort I've
seen," Christon said. "We couldn't get the ball inside early like
we wanted. My team got me the ball, and when you are a team leader
you have to want to have the ball in your hands."

	   Officials allowed some rough play in the opening-round game, and
Arkansas lost Lewis and Ruby Vaden for part of the first half with
injuries. Alabama coach Rick Moody said the physical play kept the
Crimson Tide off balance.

	 "Arkansas did a very, very good job of taking away the 3-point
shot ... knocking our heads off ... it got very physical," Moody
said.

	   Alabama made just five of 16 3-pointers and only one in the
second half. Monique Bivins scored 10 points, but only two in the
second half.

	   The Crimson Tide cut the lead to three points twice in the final
minute.

	   But Cherry's basket and a free throw by Lewis proved decisive.
Cherry added six rebounds to her 10 points despite strained
ligaments in her shooting hand.

	   In the second half, Vaden gave Arkansas a 37-35 lead -- its first
since early in the game. Her free throws with 8:15 remaining were
part of an 18-8 run to a 49-41 lead with 3 minutes to go.

	   Arkansas trailed just 27-22 at halftime despite going 9½ minutes
without a basket. After Christon gave Arkansas a 13-7 lead with
13:33 left in the half, the Lady Razorbacks made just three free
throws until Christon's 10-footer with 3:56 to go.

	   Alabama used a 15-3 run during that time to build a 22-16 lead.

	   Even with the 2:30 p.m. tipoff, the game drew an SEC tournament
first-day-record 8,513 to Alltel Arena.
